# Day 12 - Secure Data Transfer

## Task
Transfer `/tmp/nautilus.txt.gpg` from the jump host to App Server 1 and place it in `/home/nfsshare/`.

## Objective
Practice secure file transfer over SSH using the appropriate transfer method for a single-file copy.

## Commands Used
```bash
scp /tmp/nautilus.txt.gpg tony@stapp01:/home/nfsshare/
ssh tony@stapp01
ls -la /home/nfsshare/
```

## What the Commands Do
- `scp` securely copies files over SSH.
- `/tmp/nautilus.txt.gpg` is the source file on the jump host.
- `tony@stapp01:/home/nfsshare/` is the destination on App Server 1.
- `ls -la` verifies that the file was transferred successfully.

## Verification
Confirmed that `nautilus.txt.gpg` exists in `/home/nfsshare/` after transfer.

## What I Learned
- How to use `scp` for a secure one-time file copy.
- When `scp` is a better fit than `rsync` or `sftp`.
- How to verify a file transfer on the remote server.

## Personal Notes
This task reinforced that `scp` is the simplest option for moving a single file securely. For repeated syncs, `rsync` would be more efficient, while `sftp` would be better for interactive file browsing and manual transfers.
